comments.body:
@danatureguy Thank you for making me look/listen harder. I looked at the spectrogram and sure enough -- you are correct! (despite my notes -- I either mis-stated or saw both but only recorded Red-Bellied! 

I added the spectrogram above.

@danatureguy Thanks for listening. At first listen I can understand your interpretation, but their voices are a little different. There is a small population of Red-headed Woodpeckers that hangs out in Fort Hunt Park in the winter, and I have been there a couple of times specifically to record them -- as on this day. There were two flying around each other (and there are other birds in the background of course, including a Northern Flicker but the voices in the foreground (loudest/closest) were the Red-headed Woodpeckers calling and drumming.

Here is a recording from  MacAulay Library to compare it to https://search.macaulaylibrary.org/catalog?taxonCode=rehwoo&mediaType=a&q=Red-headed%20Woodpecker%20-%20Melanerpes%20erythrocephalus&user=Wil%20Hershberger

In addition, I will immediately go back to my notes to confirm!

P.S. Yes, I went back to my audio notes -- red-headed woodpecker.

results.description:
Red-bellied Woodpeckers at Fort Hunt (a unit of the George Washington Memorial Parkway), calls and drumming.

Recorded January 15, 2016 at 1:05pm with Fostex FR-2, Sennheiser ME62 with Telinga Parabola.
Trimmed, High Pass Filter (250 with 6db rolloff), and normalized at -3 according to ML best practices (in Audacity).
